Basically, I forgot that
--Top level concepts with names can actually be nested inside expression

--A method should be short, but only if it is playing the role of a method.
Definitely, the top level method there is a DSL component serving the
role of a test suite.

Overall, if the reader forgets the existence of the first few lines
and the last line,
they can read the code As if, we had @Test annotations in front of
junit methods:

#test#Test1:Test{...}
~=
@Test void test1(){...}

Yea, this perspective makes me quite happy.


The test suite organization files could look like this

MyTests:TestSuiteTree{run->Block#
  #run#tests.customers.MySuite1
  #run#tests.customers.MySuite2
  #run#tests.buldings.MySuiteTree1
  .done //or .return{Void}
}

and so on.
To 'disable' a branch, just comment the line (for now, we can add a
run.disabled method instead later)
To disable a Test/SysTest, we could have either #test.disabled
Foo:Test{...} or we could have a
DisabledTest interface to implement instead of Test.
